			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Gwen wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Heya Digcat..
<br />

<br />
I've just begun a Beastlord...  brand new to the class..  and my friend has begun as an enchantress.  So.. I was wondering.. what tips can you give me for how to group with her at these early levels..  say, through 30.
<br />

<br />
Any things I should make sure I do?  Or make sure I don't do?  Any advice on who should pull..  what our best spell combos are.. stuff like that?  Thanks,
<br />

<br />
-Gwen</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
At very low levels, the enchanter doesn't get charm and you really want him/her to use their own pet, and keep you buffed and your target unbuffed.  Its a good time to start playing with mezzing and lulling, just to see how they all work and how the BST works with them.  At times during the lower levels, you may find the enchanter of limited use.  But the investment will pay off, as when the enchanter can begin to charm creatures things become both easier and more difficult at the same time.
<br />

<br />
You need to realize that the enchanter is fairly flimsy ... you will need to get aggro without dotting (generally - you can always DoT one target as long as the enchanter knows about it) so the enchanter will not be interrupted when trying to mez and re-mez.  You may need to heal the enchanter as well, so keep an eye on them and act accordingly.  Also, the enchanter needs to get hit in order for their pet to attack, so work together to allow him to get hit so you can get the additional DPS.  The enchanter should be playing with their stuns for when monsters come after him/her.
<br />

<br />
When the enchanter can charm .. play with that when possible.  Get a handle on how it works, see what works best for how you behave in that case.  You will need to keep an eye on the enchanter, and save your own health and mana for emergencies (like when you pull two and charm breaks) - you will need to build aggro, you will need to tank a bit, and you will need to heal - all without making the mobs unmezzable with dots.  Note that your pet will be able to build up alot of aggro on any mob given time - especially with procs.
<br />

<br />
Have fun though, the enchanter/bst combo is one of the best duos in the game, imo.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
